name: pat_id
description: The Patients ID in the dataset

name: rel_time
description: The relative time since the patient has entered the ICU

name: af_vital
description: Atrial fibrillation (A-fib) is an irregular and often very rapid heart rhythm (arrhythmia) that can lead to blood clots in the heart. A-fib increases the risk of stroke, heart failure and other heart-related complications.

name: alt_labor
description: Alanine transaminase (ALT), also known as alanine aminotransferase, is an enzyme that’s mainly found in your liver, though it exists in other parts of your body.

name: ast_labor
description: AST is an enzyme that is normally present in the liver, heart, brain, pancreas, kidneys, and many other muscles and tissues in the body. Enzymes like AST help facilitate fundamental biological processes in these organs and tissues.

name: albumin_labor
description: Albumin helps move many small molecules through the blood, including bilirubin, calcium, progesterone, and medicines. It plays an important role in keeping the fluid in the blood from leaking into the tissues.

name: alpha_blocker_med
description: Alpha blockers are a type of blood pressure medication. They lower blood pressure by preventing a hormone called norepinephrine from tightening the muscles in the walls of smaller arteries and veins.

name: barbiturat_med
description: Barbiturates belong to the group of medicines called central nervous system (CNS) depressants (medicines that cause drowsiness). They act on the brain and CNS to produce effects that may be helpful or harmful.

name: basophile_labor
description: Basophils are one of the five white blood cell types that protect your body from infections or respond to intruders like parasites, fungi and cancer cells.

name: benzodiazepin_med
description: Benzodiazepines (BZD, BDZ, BZs), are a class of psychoactive drugs. As depressants—drugs which lower brain activity—they are prescribed to treat conditions such as anxiety, insomnia, and seizures.

name: bili_bga
description: Bilirubin is a red-orange compound that occurs in the normal catabolic pathway that breaks down heme in vertebrates. This catabolism is a necessary process in the body's clearance of waste products that arise from the destruction of aged or abnormal red blood cells.

name: ck_mb_labor
description: Creatine kinase MB, is a subtype of the enzyme Creatine kinase, that origins in the Heart.

name: ck_labor
description: Creatine kinase, also known as phosphocreatine kinase is an enzyme expressed by various tissue types. It catalyses the conversion of creatine to phosphocreatine, consuming adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and generating adenosine diphosphate (ADP).

name: cpp_vital
description: Cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is the net pressure gradient that drives oxygen delivery to cerebral tissue. It is the difference between the mean arterial pressure (MAP) and the intracranial pressure (ICP)

name: crp_labor
description: A type of protein that is associated with inflammation in the body, CRP is measured using a small blood sample drawn from a vein in your arm.

name: cholesterin_labor
description: Cholesterol is any of a class of certain organic molecules called lipids. It is a sterol (or modified steroid), a type of lipid. Cholesterol is biosynthesized by all animal cells and is an essential structural component of animal cell membranes. When chemically isolated, it is a yellowish crystalline solid.

name: direkter_vasodilatator_med
description: Direct vasodilators are strong medications that generally are used only when other medications haven't controlled blood pressure adequately.

name: eosinophile_labor
description: Eosinophilic cellulitis is a skin disease that presents with painful, red, raised, and warm patches of skin.[2] The rash comes on suddenly, lasts for a few weeks, and often repeatedly comes back.

name: erythrocyten_labor
description: Erythrocytes (red blood cells or RBCs) are anucleate, biconcave cells, filled with hemoglobin, that transport oxygen and carbon dioxide between the lungs and tissues.

name: fcohb_bga
description: The fraction of oxygenated haemoglobin is a parameter which is calculated from values directly measured by absorption spectrophotometry. It is expressed as

name: fio2_vital
description: Fraction of inspired oxygen is the molar or volumetric fraction of oxygen in the inhaled gas.

name: gcs_auge_vital
description: The Glasgow Coma Scale is a clinical scale used to reliably measure a person's level of consciousness after a brain injury. This is the Eye Response Test.

name: gcs_motor_vital
description: The Glasgow Coma Scale is a clinical scale used to reliably measure a person's level of consciousness after a brain injury. This is the Motor Response Test.

name: gcs_total_vital
description: The Glasgow Coma Scale is a clinical scale used to reliably measure a person's level of consciousness after a brain injury.

name: gcs_verbal_vital
description: The Glasgow Coma Scale is a clinical scale used to reliably measure a person's level of consciousness after a brain injury. This is the Verbal Response Test.

name: glu_bga
description: Glycaemia, also known as blood sugar level, blood sugar concentration, or blood glucose level is the measure of glucose concentrated in the blood of humans.

name: hco3_bga
description: blood bicarbonate (plasma bicarbonate) the bicarbonate of the blood plasma, an important parameter of acid-base balance measured in blood gas analysis.

name: harnstoff_n_labor
description: the blood urea nitrogen (BUN) test reveals important information about how well your kidneys are working. A BUN test measures the amount of urea nitrogen that's in your blood.

name: hb_bga_bga
description: A hemoglobin test measures the amount of hemoglobin in your blood. Hemoglobin is a protein in your red blood cells that carries oxygen to your body's organs and tissues and transports carbon dioxide from your organs and tissues back to your lungs.

name: icp_vital
description: Increased intracranial pressure  is a rise in pressure around your brain

name: inr_labor
description: An INR test measures the time for the blood to clot.

name: katecholamin_med
description: Catecholamines are hormones that the brain, nerve tissues, and adrenal glands produce. The body releases catecholamines in response to emotional or physical stress.

name: kreatinin_labor
description: Creatinine is a waste product that comes from the normal wear and tear on muscles of the body. Everyone has creatinine in their bloodstream.

name: ldh_labor
description: Lactate dehydrogenase is an important enzyme that helps with cellular respiration, the process through which your body transforms glucose (sugar) from the food you eat into energy for your cells.

name: leukocyten_labor
description: Leukocytes are the major cellular components of the inflammatory and immune system. While they only make up about 1 percent of the blood in the body, leukocytes play an important role in protecting the body from infections/diseases caused by various microorganisms (e.g. bacteria, amoeba etc) and other types of parasites (filarial worms etc).

name: lipase_labor
description: Lipase is a type of protein made by your pancreas, an organ located near your stomach. Lipase helps your body digest fats.

name: lymphocyten_labor
description: Lymphocytes are white blood cells and one of the body’s main types of immune cells. They are made in the bone marrow and found in the blood and lymph tissue.

name: mchc_labor
description: Measures the concentration of hemoglobin in a given volume of red blood cells. Or a more accurate definition is that MCHC expresses the average weight of hemoglobin per unit volume of red blood cell.

name: mch_labor
description: MCH value refers to the average quantity of hemoglobin present in a single red blood cell.

name: mcv_labor
description: MCV stands for mean corpuscular volume. An MCV blood test measures the average size of your red blood cells.

name: magnesium_labor
description: A magnesium blood test measures the amount of magnesium in your blood. Magnesium is a type of electrolyte. Electrolytes are electrically charged minerals that are responsible for many important functions and processes in your body.

name: monocyten_labor
description: Monocytes are a type of white blood cell in your immune system. Monocytes turn into macrophage or dendritic cells when an invading germ or bacteria enters your body. The cells either kill the invader or alert other blood cells to help destroy it and prevent infection.

name: neutrophile_labor
description: Neutrophils are a type of white blood cell that help heals damaged tissues and resolves infections. Neutrophil levels can increase or decrease in response to infections, injuries, drug treatments, certain genetic conditions, and stress.

name: opioid_med
description: Opioids are a class of drugs naturally found in the opium poppy plant and that work in the brain to produce a variety of effects, including the relief of pain with many of these drugs.

name: pco2_bga
description: Measurement of pco2 in the systemic circulation indicates the effectiveness of ventilation at the lungs' alveoli, given the diffusing capacity of the gas. It is a good indicator of respiratory function and the closely related factor of acid–base homeostasis, reflecting the amount of acid in the blood (without lactic acid).

name: peep_vital
description: Positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) is a value that can be set up in patients receiving invasive or non-invasive mechanical ventilation. This activity reviews the indications, contraindications, complications, and other key elements of the use of PEEP in the clinical setting as relates to the essential points needed by members of an interprofessional team managing the care of patients requiring assisted ventilation.

name: po2_bga
description: The concentration of OXYGEN in the blood. This commonly measured parameter is an important indicator of the efficiency with which oxygen is transferred from atmosphere to blood.

name: phosphat_labor
description: Phosphorus is an essential mineral which plays a role in many functions of the body, including the structure of bone and teeth, muscle, and nerve conductions, filtering waste out of the body, DNA and RNA synthesis, and balancing the use of certain vitamins.

name: pmean_vital
description: Mean airway pressure (Pmean) is a common pressure monitoring parameter of mechanical ventilators that is closely correlated with mean alveolar pressure and represents stresses applied to the lung parenchyma during ventilation.

name: ppeak_vital
description: Peak inspiratory pressure is the highest level of pressure applied to the lungs during inhalation

name: rass_vital
description: Richmond Agitation-Sedation Scale (RASS) is a medical scale used to measure the agitation or sedation level of a person.

name: sbe_bga
description: Standard base excess is the concentration of titrable base when the blood is titrated back to a normal plasma pH of 7.40, at a normal pCO2 ( 40 mmHg) and 37° C, at the actual oxygen saturation, AND at an "anaemic" haemoglobin concentration, to account for the buffering of extravascular fluid by haemoglobin.

name: spo2_vital
description: Healthy adults will generally have 95% – 99% oxygen saturation while any pulse oximeter readings below 89% would typically be cause for concern.

name: tsh_labor
description: The thyroid is a butterfly-shaped gland in the throat. It produces hormones that help regulate many bodily functions, such as metabolism, heart rate, and body temperature.

name: temp_vital
description: The typical temperature range found in humans. The normal human body temperature range is typically stated as 36.5–37.5 °C

name: thrombocyten_labor
description: Platelets are a component of blood whose function (along with the coagulation factors) is to react to bleeding from blood vessel injury by clumping, thereby initiating a blood clot.

name: triglyceride_labor
description: Triglycerides are the most commonTrusted Source form of fat in the body. Your body stores and uses this type of fat for energy between meals. If triglyceride levels in your blood are elevated, it could mean you’re at high risk for some health conditions.

name: troponin_labor
description: Troponins are proteins found in the cardiac muscles. When the heart is damaged, it releases troponin into the bloodstream.

name: aptt_labor
description: This is a measurement of how effective and timely the blood’s clotting process happens to be. It is typically ordered as a first option blood test when a patient presents with unexplained or uncontrolled bleeding so hemostasis can be properly evaluated.

name: diast_vital
description: The diastolic reading, is the pressure in the arteries when the heart rests between beats. This is the time when the heart fills with blood and gets oxygen.

name: ft3_labor
description: Triiodothyronine or T3 is a hormone secreted by the thyroid glands and is important for the metabolism of your body including the heart rate and temperature.

name: ft4_labor
description: Thyroxine (sometime called T4) is a hormone produced by the thyroid gland. The term “free thyroxine” means measured thyroxine that is not bound to proteins in the blood.

name: ph_bga
description: Identifying imbalances in your pH and blood gas levels can also help your doctor monitor treatment for certain conditions, such as lung and kidney diseases.

name: syst_vital
description: When your heart beats, it squeezes and pushes blood through your arteries to the rest of your body. This force creates pressure on those blood vessels, and that's your systolic blood pressure.
